:year>2015</gtr:year></gtr:disseminationOutput></gtr:disseminationOutputs><gtr:exploitationOutputs/><gtr:furtherFundingOutputs/><gtr:impactSummaryOutputs><gtr:impactSummaryOutput><gtr:description>Stakeholder Science Workshop, Colt Park (see engagement entry)</gtr:description><gtr:firstYearOfImpact>2015</gtr:firstYearOfImpact><gtr:id>9C0FDA41-FC4C-4DA3-96CA-86287E348AC6</gtr:id><gtr:impactTypes><gtr:impactType>Policy &amp; public services</gtr:impactType></gtr:impactTypes><gtr:outcomeId>5460f537827748.77567230</gtr:outcomeId><gtr:sector>Agriculture, Food and Drink,Environment</gtr:sector></gtr:impactSummaryOutput></gtr:impactSummaryOutputs><gtr:intellectualPropertyOutputs/><gtr:keyFindingsOutput><gtr:description>During a visit to the UK, Noah Ferier and Jon Leff completed a sampling of our mesocosom and field experiment of BBSRC grant BB/I009000/2. Our goal was to test, in both monocultures and mixed grassland communities, whether plant attributes were predictive of complex soil communities including fungi, bacteria, protists, and metazoa. The community composition of each taxonomic group was affected by plant species identity irrespective of whether plants were grown in monoculture or in mixed plant communities in the field. Moreover, plant community composition predicted additional variation in soil communities beyond that predicted from soil abiotic characteristics. However, neither plant phylogeny nor plant traits were strong predictors of soil communities in monocultures or mixed communities. In the field, plant community composition, quantified by measuring aboveground biomass directly and by sequencing plant DNA from soil, was predictive of soil community composition, but root-based plant community composition was not, suggesting that aboveground plant community attributes are better predictors of complex soil communities. Together, these results suggest that information on aboveground plant distributions can improve our ability to predict soil community composition, but the strength of these associations varies across taxonomic groups. In addition, these results highlight the need to identify and quantify the plant traits driving differences in soil communities in order to generalize plant-soil community relationships across landscapes and predict plant community effects on soil communities a priori.</gtr:description><gtr:exploitationPathways>The project is still ongoing but we envisage that the trait-based framework developed as part of this project will be of use for future projects testing the importance of plant traits for microbial communities in grassland and other ecosystems.</gtr:exploitationPathways><gtr:id>6BE6B4BD-D30E-44D2-ABB4-6A249BBAC648</gtr:id><gtr:outcomeId>5460f514846203.58124535</gtr:outcomeId><gtr:sectors><gtr:sector>Agriculture, Food and Drink,Environment</gtr:sector></gtr:sectors></gtr:keyFindingsOutput><gtr:otherResearchOutputs/><gtr:policyInfluenceOutputs/><gtr:productOutputs/><gtr:researchDatabaseAndModelOutputs/><gtr:researchMaterialOutputs/><gtr:softwareAndTechnicalProductOutputs/><gtr:spinOutOutputs/></gtr:output><gtr:publications><gtr:publication><gtr:id>4BB8431C-DA5C-4AEB-A6E3-699226856EFF</gtr:id><gtr:title>A global atlas of the dominant bacteria found in soil.</gtr:title><gtr:parentPublicationTitle>Science (New York, N.Y.)</gtr:parentPublicationTitle><gtr:authors><gtr:author url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/person/80a244f1a5bc1f25aa56c1d7ede0daf0"><gtr:id>80a244f1a5bc1f25aa56c1d7ede0daf0</gtr:id><gtr:otherNames>Delgado-Baquerizo M</gtr:otherNames></gtr:author></gtr:authors><gtr:date>2018-01-01</gtr:date><gtr:issn>0036-8075</gtr:issn><gtr:outcomeId>5a9d1437e4c0a8.05653960</gtr:outcomeId></gtr:publication><gtr:publication><gtr:id>F06B00A3-C2BB-43A5-8582-9E88959E3B0F</gtr:id><gtr:title>Plant trait-based approaches for interrogating belowground function</gtr:title><gtr:parentPublicationTitle>Biology and Environment: Proceedings of the Royal Irish Academy</gtr:parentPublicationTitle><gtr:authors><